							<h4>Evaluating Information on the Internet</h4>
							<p>It is extremely important to learn how to evaluate information found on the Internet. Since the Web and the Internet are so free and open, anyone can make a Web site about any topic. However, just because you read something on a Web site or receive it in your email, even when it looks credible (trustworthy, believable) does not make it so.</p>	
							<p>To help you in the evaluation process, go to your Testing USB drive and bring up a checklist.</p>
							<p>The Testing USB drive will be referred to here as X: even though the actual drive letter for it will be different on your computer.</p>							
							<p>Double click on the WebChecklist.pdf from X:\DIDL\ECfiles\Workfiles\Internet and it will open. Print out two copies of it.</p>							
							<p>Notice that the checklist has four sections:</p>
								<ol>
									<li><strong>Authority -</strong> Who is the author (person or company) of the site?</li>
									<li><strong>Content -</strong> What information is on the site?</li>
									<li><strong>Reputation -</strong> What do others say about the site?</li>
									<li><strong>Verdict -</strong> Reviewing the above, is this a credible site?</li>
								</ol>							
							<p>Print and read through the following page:</p>							
							<a href="http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/TeachingLib/Guides/Internet/Evaluate.html">http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/TeachingLib/Guides/Internet/Evaluate.html</a>

<hr>							<p>Notice that the page has the following steps on it:</p>
								<ol>
									<li>What can the URL tell you?</li>
									<li>Scan the perimeter of the page...</li>
									<li>Look for indicators of quality information</li>
									<li>What do others say?</li>
									<li>Does it all add up?</li>
								</ol>							
